%p
  The Forbidden City lies in the center of Beijing, but inside you hear nothing of the busy streets. The only way you are reminded you're in the city is by the skyscrapers that pop up every once in a while.
= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-32.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '729')
= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-33.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '730')
= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-34.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '729')
%p
  The trick to get some people free shots is go exactly the opposite way of the large tours that walk by every few seconds.

= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-35.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '729')
= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-36.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '729')
%p
  You used to be able to exit at all gates, but because of the crowds, the Forbidden City is a one-way deal. This means street vendors know exactly where you'll be.
= photo(:src => '//cdn.matsimitsu.com/asia2014/day-three/day-two-37.jpg', :width => '1100', :height => '729')

%p The way back to our hotel is around the Forbidden city. The vibe here is awesome.

